1 Section 2. KRS 64.5278 is amended to read as follows:
2 (1) Any city may elect, by adopting an ordinance meeting the requirements of this
3 section, to establish an incentive program for city officers to obtain educational
4 training related to their duties and responsibilities as city officers and the functions
5 of city governments.
6 (2) The ordinance shall apply to all elected city officers within the city, and the city
7 may allow any nonelected city officer holding an office existing or created under
8 KRS 83A.080 to participate in the incentive program.
9 (3) The ordinance shall establish[designate] a base [training ]incentive [payment
10 ]amount that shall be awarded to the city officer for the completion of a training
11 unit during service as a city officer within the city. The city may establish a
12 different[This] base incentive [payment ]amount for each type of city officer
13 covered under the ordinance[shall be no less than one hundred dollars ($100) and
14 no more than five hundred dollars ($500)]. The base[training] incentive [payment
15 ]amount established in the ordinance shall not be adjusted by any index reporting
16 changes to consumer prices or any other method to account for inflation.
17 (4) The ordinance shall require city officers to complete a number of continuing
18 education hours equal to at least one (1) training unit during each calendar year in
19 order to receive a training incentive payment.
20 (5) The ordinance shall state that the city shall award the training incentive payment to
21 the city officer for the completion of a training unit during the calendar year. The
22 training incentive payment awarded shall be the base [training ]incentive
23 amount[payment] multiplied by the training incentive multiplier earned by the city
24 officer. The city officer shall accumulate no more than one (1) training incentive
25 multiplier per calendar year of continuous service, for a maximum of four (4)
26 training incentive multipliers.
27 (6) The ordinance shall provide that a city officer who fails to earn at least one (1)
Page 2 of 12
SB002020.100 - 876 - XXXX 3/31/2026 3:54 PM Engrossed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS SB 20/EN
1 training unit in any calendar year shall receive no training incentive payment for
2 that calendar year and shall have his or her training incentive multiplier reset to one
3 (1) for the following year.
4 (7) The ordinance may permit the city officer to carry forward no more than fifteen
5 (15) hours of excess credit hours earned in one (1) calendar year to apply to the
6 minimum fifteen (15) hours training unit required in the next calendar year.[
7 "Excess hours" means credit hours earned beyond fifteen (15) during a single
8 calendar year.]
9 (8) The ordinance shall require the city officer to present proof of his or her completion
10 of the annual training unit and shall establish the time that the city officers shall
11 receive their training incentive payments.
12 (9) Each city shall, in the ordinance establishing the city officers training program,
13 establish a policy regarding the reimbursement to the city officer, or payment to the
14 provider for the city officer's attendance of an event hosting a course where the
15 officer seeks to earn credit.
16 (10) The ordinance shall specify criteria for the presentation of proof of attendance by
17 city officers and the criteria for the evaluation of a course's relevance to the duties
18 and functions of city officers and the functions of city governments. In addition to
19 other courses that may be deemed relevant by the city, courses that provide
20 instruction on statutory powers and duties of cities and city officers,
21 intergovernmental relationships, municipal finance and budgeting, municipal
22 taxation, ethics, open records, open meetings, economic development, or municipal
23 police powers shall satisfy the criteria established in the ordinance.
24 Section 3. KRS 45A.380 is amended to read as follows:
25 A local public agency may contract or purchase through noncompetitive negotiation only
26 when a written determination is made that competition is not feasible and it is further
27 determined in writing by a designee of the local public agency that:
Page 3 of 12
SB002020.100 - 876 - XXXX 3/31/2026 3:54 PM Engrossed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS SB 20/EN
1 (1) An emergency exists which will cause public harm as a result of the delay in
2 competitive procedures;
3 (2) There is a single source within a reasonable geographical area of the product or
4 service to be procured;
5 (3) The contract is for the services of a licensed professional, such as attorney,
6 physician, psychiatrist, psychologist, certified public accountant, registered nurse,
7 or educational specialist; a technician such as a plumber, electrician, carpenter, or
8 mechanic; or an artist such as a sculptor, aesthetic painter, or musician, provided,
9 however, that this provision shall not apply to architects or engineers providing
10 construction management services rather than professional architect or engineer
11 services;
12 (4) The contract is for the purchase of perishable foods, such as meat, fish, poultry, egg
13 products, fresh vegetables, and fresh fruits;
14 (5) The contract is for replacement parts where the need cannot be reasonably
15 anticipated and stockpiling is not feasible;
16 (6) The contract is for proprietary items for resale;
17 (7) In school districts the contract relates to an enterprise in which the buying or selling
18 by students is a part of the educational experience;
19 (8) The contract or purchase is for expenditures made on authorized trips outside of the
20 boundaries of the local public agency;
21 (9) The contract is for the purchase of supplies which are sold at public auction or by
22 receiving sealed bids;
23 (10) The contract is for group life insurance, group health and accident insurance, group
24 professional liability insurance, worker's compensation insurance, and
25 unemployment insurance;
26 (11) The contract is for a sale of supplies at reduced prices that will afford a purchase at
27 savings to the local public agency;[ or]
Page 4 of 12
SB002020.100 - 876 - XXXX 3/31/2026 3:54 PM Engrossed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS SB 20/EN
1 (12) The contract is with a private real estate developer and contains a requirement:
2 (a) That the developer increase the size or otherwise improve the collection
3 capacity of the sanitary sewer or storm water pipe serving the affected private
4 real estate development; and
5 (b) That the local public agency pay only the proportional cost of increasing the
6 size, or otherwise improving the collection capacity, of the sanitary sewer or
7 storm water pipe over the original collection capacity; or
8 (13) The contract is for the purchase of used vehicles or used equipment and the
9 purchase price does not exceed seventy-five percent (75%) of the manufacturer's
10 suggested retail price for the model year for a vehicle or date of manufacture for
11 equipment for the same or similar vehicles or equipment.
12 Section 4. KRS 424.260 is amended to read as follows:
13 (1) Except where a statute specifically fixes a larger sum as the minimum for a
14 requirement of advertisement for bids, a[no] city, county, or district, or board or
15 commission of a city or county, or sheriff or county clerk, shall not[may] make a
16 contract, lease, or other agreement for:
17 (a) Materials;
18 (b) Supplies, except for supplies that are:
19 1. Perishable foods such as meat, poultry, fish, egg products, fresh
20 vegetables, and fresh fruits; or
21 2. Sold at public auction;
22 (c) Equipment, except used vehicles and used equipment if the purchase price
23 does not exceed seventy-five percent (75%) of the manufacturer's suggested
24 retail price for the model year for a vehicle or date of manufacture for
25 equipment for the same or similar vehicles or equipment; or
26 (d) Contractual services other than professional;
27 involving an expenditure of more than forty thousand dollars ($40,000) without first
Page 5 of 12
SB002020.100 - 876 - XXXX 3/31/2026 3:54 PM Engrossed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS SB 20/EN
1 making newspaper advertisement for bids. This subsection shall not apply to the
2 transfer of property between governmental agencies as authorized in KRS
3 82.083(4)(a).
4 (2) If the fiscal court requires that the sheriff or county clerk advertise for bids on
5 expenditures of less than forty thousand dollars ($40,000), the fiscal court
6 requirement shall prevail.
7 (3) (a) Nothing in this statute shall limit or restrict the ability of a local school district
8 to acquire supplies and equipment outside of the bidding procedure if those
9 supplies and equipment meet the specifications of the contracts awarded by
10 the Office of Material and Procurement Services in the Office of the
11 Controller within the Finance and Administration Cabinet or a federal, local,
12 or cooperative agency and are available for purchase elsewhere at a lower
13 price. A board of education may purchase those supplies and equipment
14 without advertising for bids if, prior to making the purchases, the board of
15 education obtains certification from the district's finance or purchasing officer
16 that the items to be purchased meet the standards and specifications fixed by
17 state price contract, federal (GSA) price contract, or the bid of another school
18 district whose bid specifications allow other districts to utilize their bids, and
19 that the sales price is lower than that established by the various price contract
20 agreements or available through the bid of another school district whose bid
21 specifications would allow the district to utilize their bid.
22 (b) The procedures set forth in paragraph (a) of this subsection shall not be
23 available to the district for any specific item once the bidding procedure has
24 been initiated by an invitation to bid and a publication of specifications for
25 that specific item has been published. In the event that all bids are rejected,
26 the district may again avail itself of the provisions of paragraph (a) of this
27 subsection.
